# Full end-to-end checkout flow
#
# Run each ### block IN ORDER — variables captured from one step are used in the next.
# The REST Client keeps @variables alive for the lifetime of the file session.
#
# Flow:
#   Step 1  POST /v1/checkout          → BFF: payment stub + orders-api + Redis cache
#   Step 2  GET  /v1/checkout/:id      → BFF: reads checkout session from Redis
#   Step 3  GET  /v1/orders/:id        → orders-api: confirms order exists in Postgres
#   Step 4  GET  /v1/customer/orders   → BFF: cache miss → orders-api → cache (30s)
#   Step 5  GET  /v1/customer/orders   → BFF: cache hit (same request within 30s)
#   Step 6  PATCH /v1/orders/:id       → orders-api: pending → confirmed (writes outbox)
#   Step 7  PATCH /v1/orders/:id       → orders-api: confirmed → shipped (writes outbox)
#   Step 8  GET  /notifier/readyz      → verify notifier-worker consumed the events
#   Step 9  GET  /notifier/metrics     → check consumer lag dropped to 0

@ordersApiUrl      = {{$dotenv ordersApiUrl}}
@checkoutBffUrl    = {{$dotenv checkoutBffUrl}}
@notifierWorkerUrl = {{$dotenv notifierWorkerUrl}}
@apiKey            = {{$dotenv apiKey}}
@jwtToken          = {{$dotenv jwtToken}}

# ── Step 1: Create checkout ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Expected: 201 Created
# Side effects:
#   - payment stub runs in-process (~300ms, 2% chance of 402)
#   - POST /v1/orders called on orders-api with retry policy (up to 2 retries on 5xx)
#   - Postgres: INSERT orders + order_items + outbox(order.created) + idempotency_keys (atomic tx)
#   - Redis: SET checkout:{checkoutId} (TTL 3600s)
# @name step1_createCheckout
POST {{checkoutBffUrl}}/v1/checkout
Authorization: Bearer {{jwtToken}}
Idempotency-Key: {{$guid}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "currency": "USD",
  "items": [
    { "sku": "WIDGET-001", "qty": 2, "unit_price_cents": 1999 },
    { "sku": "GADGET-007", "qty": 1, "unit_price_cents": 4999 }
  ]
}

@checkoutId = {{step1_createCheckout.response.body.$.checkout_id}}
@orderId    = {{step1_createCheckout.response.body.$.order_id}}

### Step 2: Retrieve checkout session from Redis
# Expected: 200 with the session (checkout_id, order_id, status, total_cents)
# This never touches Postgres — Redis only.
# If you see 404 here, the order in Step 1 failed.
GET {{checkoutBffUrl}}/v1/checkout/{{checkoutId}}

### Step 3: Verify the order exists in Postgres (direct orders-api call)
# Expected: 200 with status "pending"
# status=pending is the initial state — the BFF doesn't auto-confirm the order.
GET {{ordersApiUrl}}/v1/orders/{{orderId}}
X-Api-Key: {{apiKey}}

### Step 4: List customer orders via BFF — first call (cache MISS)
# Expected: 200, x-cache: MISS header
# orders-api is called, result cached in Redis for 30s under
# key customer:{customerId}:orders:page=1:size=10
# @name step4_listOrdersMiss
GET {{checkoutBffUrl}}/v1/customer/orders?page=1&size=10
Authorization: Bearer {{jwtToken}}

### Step 5: Same list again — should be cache HIT
# Expected: 200, x-cache: HIT header (no Postgres or orders-api call)
# Run within 30 seconds of Step 4 to see the HIT.
GET {{checkoutBffUrl}}/v1/customer/orders?page=1&size=10
Authorization: Bearer {{jwtToken}}

### Step 6: Confirm the order (pending → confirmed)
# Expected: 200 with status "confirmed"
# Side effects:
#   - Postgres: UPDATE orders SET status='confirmed' + INSERT outbox(order.confirmed) (atomic tx)
#   - OutboxPublisher (background, ~1s delay): XADD orders.events with event_type=order.confirmed
#   - notifier-worker: XREADGROUP picks it up, POSTs to WEBHOOK_URL
PATCH {{ordersApiUrl}}/v1/orders/{{orderId}}
X-Api-Key: {{apiKey}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "status": "confirmed",
  "reason": "payment verified"
}

### Step 7: Ship the order (confirmed → shipped)
# Expected: 200 with status "shipped"
# Side effects: same outbox pattern, emits order.shipped event to Redis stream
PATCH {{ordersApiUrl}}/v1/orders/{{orderId}}
X-Api-Key: {{apiKey}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "status": "shipped",
  "reason": "dispatched via courier"
}

### Step 8: Verify order final state
# Expected: 200 with status "shipped"
GET {{ordersApiUrl}}/v1/orders/{{orderId}}
X-Api-Key: {{apiKey}}

### Step 9: Check notifier-worker readiness (consumer group joined + heartbeat fresh)
# Expected: 200 { "status": "ready" }
# If 503, the worker lost its Redis connection or the heartbeat went stale.
GET {{notifierWorkerUrl}}/readyz

### Step 10: Check consumer lag
# Expected: notifier_consumer_lag 0 (all events processed)
# If lag > 0, the webhook is failing or the worker is behind.
# Look for these metrics:
#   notifier_consumer_lag
#   notifier_events_consumed_total{event_type="order.created",status="success"}
#   notifier_events_consumed_total{event_type="order.confirmed",status="success"}
#   notifier_events_consumed_total{event_type="order.shipped",status="success"}
GET {{notifierWorkerUrl}}/metrics

### Step 11: Cache is now stale — re-list to confirm shipped status appears
# Expected: 200, x-cache: MISS (previous 30s cache has expired if you waited, or HIT with stale data)
GET {{checkoutBffUrl}}/v1/customer/orders?page=1&size=10
Authorization: Bearer {{jwtToken}}

# ── Bonus: Replay protection ──────────────────────────────────────────────────

### Replay the same checkout with the same Idempotency-Key → should return cached 201
# The BFF doesn't enforce idempotency itself — orders-api does.
# The BFF will call orders-api again with the same key, which returns the cached order.
POST {{checkoutBffUrl}}/v1/checkout
Authorization: Bearer {{jwtToken}}
Idempotency-Key: {{step1_createCheckout.request.headers.Idempotency-Key}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "currency": "USD",
  "items": [
    { "sku": "WIDGET-001", "qty": 2, "unit_price_cents": 1999 },
    { "sku": "GADGET-007", "qty": 1, "unit_price_cents": 4999 }
  ]
}
